description.value: Bright blue glazed composition scarab: engraved on the base in three registers. In the upper register is the lower end of a cartouche containing the name of a king. Behind the cartouche appear the legs of a bird, possibly a falcon. In the lower register is Horus as a bird-headed human presenting the 'w?s'-sceptre to Sekhmet(?); another lion or cat-headed goddess stands behind Horus holding a flower on a long stalk. Very intricate design in a small space. Hole pierced through longitudinally. Section of base chipped away.

description.value: Comparatively large and fine scarab, made of glazed steatite, completely preserved. Remains of white ground preserved, few traces of a very light blue glaze, the steatite is beige.  The division between head and prothorax is shown with a single line. The division between prothorax and elytra is shown in a single line as is the suture. The humeral callosities are indicated by a small carved triangle.  The shape of the head is oval, no eyes indicated. The clypeus shows remains of three grooves, dividing it into four lobes. The plates at the sides are shown as well.  The side of the scarab shows three finely carved legs on each side that show details of hairs in small grooves on all legs. Seen from the side, the legs are sitting on a base plate. description.value: Chalcedony gem; representation of Silenos. Oval amethyst gem; pierced; in modern setting. Openwork scarab of green jasper. Single-line field divider. Executed in, or imitating, Mesopotamian drilled style, a Babylonian-looking bearded worshipper in a long, girded garment gestures before a goddess with cylindrical head-dress surmounted by a small globe, seated on a star-studded throne; ankh between them, eight-pointed star with dots between the rays above; one line inscription in exergue with last letter in field. Carnelian scarab engraved with Herakles holding a club and reclining on a raft, buoyed up by five amphorae. Black steatite pectoral in the shape of a naos with heart scarab for a royal documents scribe, Pyay; a representation of a scarab with speckled pronotum and striated elytra projects from the face, flanked by incised representations of Isis and Nephthys highlighted in white; incised Hieroglyphic text on the reverse within an oval panel and on the 'lintel' and 'jambs' as well as two wedjat-eyes; pierced twice obliquely through the top edge.
